






@h Version A

@(1.1 = 1-26) In those days, in those distant days, in those nights, in those remote nights, in those years, in those distant years; in days of yore, when the necessary things had been brought into manifest existence, in days of yore, when the necessary things had been for the first time properly cared for, when bread had been tasted for the first time in the shrines of the Land, when the ovens of the Land had been made to work, when the heavens had been separated from the earth, when the earth had been delimited from the heavens, when the fame of mankind had been established, when @wDN{An} had taken the heavens for himself, when @wDN{Enlil} had taken the earth for himself, when the nether world had been given to @wDN{Ereškigala} as a gift; when he set sail, when he set sail, when the father set sail for the nether world, when @wDN{Enki} set sail for the nether world -- against the king a storm of small hailstones arose, against @wDN{Enki} a storm of large hailstones arose. The small ones were light hammers, the large ones were like stones from catapults (?). The keel of @wDN{Enki's} little boat was trembling as if it were being butted by turtles, the waves at the bow of the boat rose to devour the king like wolves and the waves at the stern of the boat were attacking @wDN{Enki} like a lion.

@(1.27 = 27-35) At that time, there was a single tree, a single @fsux{ḫalub} tree, a single tree, growing on the bank of the pure @wWN{Euphrates}, being watered by the @wWN{Euphrates}. The force of the south wind uprooted it and stripped its branches, and the @wWN{Euphrates} picked it up and carried it away. A woman, respectful of @wDN{An's} words, was walking along; a woman, respectful of @wDN{Enlil's} words, was walking along, and took the tree and brought it into @wSN{Unug}, into @wDN{Inana's} luxuriant garden.

@(1.36 = 36-46) The woman planted the tree with her feet, but not with her hands. The woman watered it using her feet but not her hands. She said: @q[Inana,]{“When will this be a luxuriant chair on which I can take a seat?”} She said: @q[Inana,]{“When this will be a luxuriant bed on which I can lie down?”} Five years, 10 years went by, the tree grew massive; its bark, however, did not split. At its roots, a snake immune to incantations made itself a nest. In its branches, the Anzud bird settled its young. In its trunk, the phantom maid built herself a dwelling, the maid who laughs with a joyful heart. But holy @wDN{Inana} cried!

@(1.47 = 47-69) When dawn was breaking, when the horizon became bright, when the little birds, at the break of dawn, began to clamour, when @wDN{Utu} had left his bedchamber, his sister holy @wDN{Inana} said to the young warrior @wDN{Utu}: @q[Inana,Utu]{“My brother, in those days when destiny was determined, when abundance overflowed in the Land, when @wDN{An} had taken the heavens for himself, when @wDN{Enlil} had taken the earth for himself, when the nether world had been given to @wDN{Ereškigala} as a gift; when he set sail, when he set sail, when the father set sail for the nether world, when @wDN{Enki} set sail for the nether world -- against the lord a storm of small hailstones arose, against @wDN{Enki} a storm of large hailstones arose. The small ones were light hammers, the large ones were like stones from catapults (?). The keel of @wDN{Enki's} little boat was trembling as if it were being butted by turtles, the waves at the bow of the boat rose to devour the lord like wolves and the waves at the stern of the boat were attacking @wDN{Enki} like a lion.”}

@(1.70 = 70-78) @q{“At that time, there was a single tree, a single @fsux{ḫalub} tree, a single tree (?), growing on the bank of the pure @wWN{Euphrates}, being watered by the @wWN{Euphrates}. The force of the south wind uprooted it and stripped its branches, and the @wWN{Euphrates} picked it up and carried it away. I, a woman, respectful of @wDN{An's} words, was walking along; I, a woman, respectful of @wDN{Enlil's} words, was walking along, and took the tree and brought it into @wSN{Unug}, into holy @wDN{Inana's} luxuriant garden.”}

@(1.79 = 79-90) @q{“I, the woman, planted the tree with my feet, but not with my hands. I, 
{@wDN{Inana}} {@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} the woman
} , watered it using my feet but not my hands. She said: @q[Inana,]{“When will this be a luxuriant chair on which I can take a seat?”} She said: @q[Inana,]{“When will this be a luxuriant bed on which I can lie down?”} Five years, 10 years had gone by, the tree had grown massive; its bark, however, did not split. At its roots, a snake immune to incantations made itself a nest. In its branches, the Anzud bird settled its young. In its trunk, the phantom maid built herself a dwelling, the maid who laughs with a joyful heart. But holy @wDN{Inana} cried!”} Her brother, the young warrior @wDN{Utu}, however, did not stand by her in the matter.


@(1.91 = 91-113) When dawn was breaking, when the horizon became bright, when the little birds, at the break of dawn, began to clamour, when @wDN{Utu} had left his bedchamber, his sister holy @wDN{Inana} said to the warrior @wDN{Gilgameš}: @q[Inana,Gilgamec]{“My brother, in those days when destiny was determined, when abundance overflowed in the Land, when @wDN{An} had taken the heavens for himself, when @wDN{Enlil} had taken the earth for himself, when the nether world had been given to @wDN{Ereškigala} as a gift; when he set sail, when he set sail, when the father set sail for the nether world, when @wDN{Enki} set sail for the nether world -- against the lord a storm of small hailstones arose, against @wDN{Enki} a storm of large hailstones arose. The small ones were light hammers, the large ones were like stones from catapults (?). The keel of @wDN{Enki's} little boat was trembling as if it were being butted by turtles, the waves at the bow of the boat rose to devour the lord like wolves and the waves at the stern of the boat were attacking @wDN{Enki} like a lion.”}

@(1.114 = 114-122) @q{“At that time, there was a single tree, a single @fsux{ḫalub} tree, a single tree (?), growing on the bank of the pure @wWN{Euphrates}, being watered by the @wWN{Euphrates}. The force of the south wind uprooted it and stripped its branches, and the @wWN{Euphrates} picked it up and carried it away. I, a woman, respectful of @wDN{An's} words, was walking along; I, a woman, respectful of @wDN{Enlil's} words, was walking along, and took the tree and brought it into @wSN{Unug}, into @wDN{Inana's} luxuriant garden.”}

@(1.123 = 123-135) @q{“The woman planted the tree with her feet, but not with her hands. @wDN{Inana} watered it using her feet but not her hands. She said: @q[Inana,]{“When will this be a luxuriant chair on which I can take a seat?”} She said: @q[Inana,]{“When will this be a luxuriant bed on which I can lie down?”} Five years, 10 years had gone by, the tree had grown massive; its bark, however, did not split. At its roots, a snake immune to incantations made itself a nest. In its branches, the Anzud bird settled its young. In its trunk, the phantom maid built herself a dwelling, the maid who laughs with a joyful heart. But 
{holy @wDN{Inana}} {@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} I, holy @wDN{Inana},
}  cried!”} In the matter which his sister had told him about, her brother, the warrior @wDN{Gilgameš}, stood by her.


@(1.136 = 136-150) He 
{strapped
} 
{@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} ……
}  his …… belt of 50 minas weight to his waist -- 50 minas were to him as 30 shekels. He took his bronze axe used for expeditions, which weighs seven talents and seven minas, in his hand. He killed the snake immune to incantations living at its roots. The Anzud bird living in its branches took up its young and went into the mountains. The phantom maid living in its trunk left (?) her dwelling and sought refuge in the wilderness. As for the tree, he uprooted it and stripped its branches, and the sons of his city, who went with him, cut up its branches and 
{bundled them
} 
{@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} piled them up
} . He gave it to his sister holy @wDN{Inana} for her chair. He gave it to her for her bed. As for himself, from its roots, he manufactured his ball (?) and, from its branches, he manufactured his mallet (?).


@(1.151 = 151-165) He played with the ball (?) in the broad square, never wanting to stop playing it, and he praised himself in the broad square, never wanting to stop praising himself. 
{@noteanchor{mss. from Urim add:} The young men of his city were playing with the ball (?).
}  For (?) him who made the team of the widows' children ……, they lamented: @q{“O my neck! O my hips!”} For those that had a mother, the mother brought bread for her son; for those that had a sister, the sister poured water for her brother. As the evening came, he marked the spot where the ball (?) had been placed, and he picked up his ball (?) from in front of him and took it home. But early in the morning as he …… the place marked, the widows' accusation and the young girls' complaint caused his ball (?) and his mallet (?) to fall down to the bottom of the nether world. 
{@noteanchor{1 ms. adds:} He could not reach them by …….
}  He tried with his hand but could not 
{reach
} 
{@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} touch
}  them, tried with his foot but could not 
{reach
} 
{@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} touch
}  them.


@(1.166 = 166-175) At the gate of @wGN{Ganzer}, in front of the nether world, he sat down. @wDN{Gilgameš} wept, crying bitterly: @q[Gilgamec,]{“O my ball (?)! O my mallet (?)! O my ball (?), I am still not satiated with its charms, the game with it has not yet palled for me! If only my ball (?) waited still in the carpenter's house for me! I would treat the carpenter's wife like my own mother -- if only it waited still there for me! I would treat the carpenter's child like my little sister -- if only it waited still there for me! 
{My ball (?) has fallen down to the nether world -- who will retrieve it for me?
} {@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} Who will retrieve my ball (?) from the nether world?
} {My mallet (?) has fallen down to @wGN{Ganzer} -- who will retrieve it for me?
} {@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} Who will retrieve my mallet (?) from @wGN{Ganzer}?
} ”}


@(1.176 = 176-183) His servant @wPN{Enkidu} 
{answered
} 
{@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} said to
}  
{him
} 
{@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} @wDN{Gilgameš}
} : @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“My king, you weep; why does your heart worry? Today I shall retrieve your ball (?) from the nether world, I shall retrieve your mallet (?) from @wGN{Ganzer}.”} @wDN{Gilgameš} answered @wPN{Enkidu}: @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“{If today
} {@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} If
}  you are going to go down to the nether world, let me advise you! My instructions should be followed. Let me talk to you! 
{Pay attention to my words
} {@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} My words should be followed
} !”}


@(1.184 = 184-198) @q{“You should not put on your clean garments: they would recognise immediately that you are alien. You should not anoint yourself with fine oil from a bowl: they would surround you at 
{its
} {@noteanchor{1 ms. has instead:} your
}  scent. You should not hurl throw-sticks in the nether world: those struck down by the throw-sticks would surround you. You should not not hold a cornel-wood stick in your hand: the spirits would feel insulted by you. You should not put sandals on your feet. You should not shout in the nether world. You should not kiss your beloved wife. You should not hit your wife even if you are annoyed with her. You should not kiss your beloved child. You should not hit your son even if you are annoyed with him. The outcry aroused would detain you in the nether world.”}


@(1.199 = 199-204) @q{“She who lies there, she who lies there, @wDN{Ninazu's} mother who lies there -- her pure shoulders are not covered with a garment, and no linen is spread over her pure breast. She has fingers like a pickaxe, she plucks her hair out like leeks.”}


@(1.205 = 205-220) @wPN{Enkidu}, however, did not heed not his master's words. He put on his clean garments and they recognised that he was alien. He anointed himself with fine oil from a bowl and they surrounded him at its scent. He hurled throw-sticks in the nether world and those struck down by the throw-sticks surrounded him. He held a cornel-wood stick in his hand and the spirits felt insulted by him. He put sandals on his feet. He caused irritation in the nether world. He kissed his beloved wife and hit his wife when he was annoyed with her. He kissed his beloved child and hit his son when he was annoyed with him. He aroused an outcry and was detained in the nether world.

@(1.221 = 221-229) The warrior @wDN{Gilgameš}, son of @wDN{Ninsumun}, directed his steps on his own to @wTN{E-kur}, the temple of @wDN{Enlil}. He cried before @wDN{Enlil}: @q[Gilgamec,Enlil]{“Father @wDN{Enlil}, my ball (?) fell down into the nether world, my mallet (?) fell down into @wGN{Ganzer}. @wPN{Enkidu} went down to retrieve them but the nether world has seized him. @wDN{Namtar} did not seize him, the Asag did not seize him; but the nether world has seized him. The @fsux{udug} demon of @wDN{Nergal}, who spares nobody, did not seize him, but the nether world has seized him. He did not fall in battle on the field of manhood, but the nether world has seized him.”} Father @wDN{Enlil} did not stand by him in the matter, so he went to @wSN{Eridug}.

@(1.230 = 230-237) In @wSN{Eridug} he directed his steps on his own to the temple of @wDN{Enki}. He cried before @wDN{Enki}: @q[Gilgamec,Enki]{“Father @wDN{Enki}, my ball (?) fell down into the nether world, my mallet (?) fell down into @wGN{Ganzer}. @wPN{Enkidu} went down to retrieve them but the nether world has seized him. @wDN{Namtar} did not seize him, the Asag did not seize him; but the nether world has seized him. The @fsux{udug} demon of @wDN{Nergal}, who spares nobody, did not seize him, but the nether world has seized him. He did not fall in battle on the field of manhood, but the nether world has seized him.”} Father @wDN{Enki} stood by him in this matter.

@(1.238 = 238-242) He said to the young warrior @wDN{Utu}, the son born by @wDN{Ningal}: @q[Enki,Utu]{“Open a hole in the nether world immediately, and then bring up his servant from the nether world!”} He opened a hole in the nether world and brought up his servant with his breeze (?) from the nether world.

@(1.243 = 243-253) They hugged and kissed. They wearied each other with questions: @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see the order of the nether world? -- If only you would tell me, my friend, if only you would tell me!”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“If I tell you the order of the nether world, sit down and weep! I shall sit down and weep! ……, which your heart rejoiced to touch, is ……, worms infest it like an old garment (?); like …… of (?) a crevice, it is full of dust.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Alas!”} he said and sat down in the dust.

@(1.254 = 254-267) @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see him who had one son?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“He weeps bitterly at the wooden peg which was driven into his wall.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see him who had two sons?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“He sits on a couple of bricks, eating bread.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see him who had three sons?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“He drinks water from a saddle waterskin.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see him who had four sons?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“His heart rejoices like a man who has four asses to yoke.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see him who had five sons?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“Like a good scribe he is indefatigable, he enters the palace easily.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see him who had six sons?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“He is a cheerful as a ploughman.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see him who had seven sons?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“As a companion of the gods, he sits on a throne and listens to judgments.”}

@(1.268 = 268-285) @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see the palace eunuch?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“Like a useless @fsux{alala} stick he is propped in a corner.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see the woman who never gave birth?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw her.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does she fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“Like a …… pot, she is thrown away violently, she gives no man joy.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see the young man who never undressed his wife?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“You finish a rope, and he weeps over the rope.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see the young woman who never undressed her husband?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw her.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does she fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“You finish a reed mat, and she weeps over the reed mat.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“Did you see him who had no heir?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“Like him who …… bricks (?), he eats bread.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“……?”} @q[Enkidu,Gilgamec]{“I saw him.”} @q[Gilgamec,Enkidu]{“How does he fare?”}

